 Wright's Native Son, Herbert traces a gender ideology of dominance and submission, its persistence in masculine subcultures like the military and big-time football, and its debilitating effects on imaginations and lives in our own day. In materials as diverse as Hannah Foster's post-Revolutionary War novel The Coquette and the Coen brothers' 1996 movie Fargo, this book taps into popular culture and high art alike to outline the logic of American manhood's violent streak--and its dire consequences for a culture with truly democratic and egalitarian ambitions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aMasculinityzUnited States. 0aMenzUnited StatesxPsychology. 0aSex rolezUnited States. 0aViolence in menzUnited States. 0aWomenxViolence againstzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Popular Culture.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674273641zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674273641423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674273641/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK